{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627784","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627784"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:53:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17153"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17153","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17153"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.03,0.03,0.5,0.2]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112953"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9843"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17153"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9870"},{"type":"tags","id":"9872"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23065"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46466"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112953","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112953"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA person who is 170 cm tall moves from a lying to a standing position. Blood pressure measurements are taken at the level of the brain. The vertical distance between their heart and brain is 25 cm.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effect of hydrostatic forces on cerebral blood pressure in the standing position?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Decreased by approximately 50-60 mmHg","Increased by approximately 50-60 mmHg","Increased by approximately 15-20 mmHg","Decreased by approximately 15-20 mmHg","Remains unchanged from lying position"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhen moving from lying to standing, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral blood pressure decreases by approximately 15-20 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E due to hydrostatic forces. This follows the equation P = \u03c1gh, where:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u03c1 (rho) = density of blood\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eg = gravitational acceleration (9.81 m/s\u00b2)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003Eh = height of the fluid column (vertical distance between heart and brain)\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor example, with blood density of 1050 kg/m\u00b3 and approximate heart-to-brain distance of 25 cm: P = 1050 \u00d7 9.81 \u00d7 0.25 = 2575 Pa \u2248 19 mmHg\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased by approximately 15-20 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - Pressure decreases rather than increases above the heart due to gravitational effects\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemains unchanged from lying position\u003C/strong\u003E - Hydrostatic forces definitely affect blood pressure when position changes\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased by approximately 50-60 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - This magnitude of decrease is too large for the typical height difference between heart and brain\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased by approximately 50-60 mmHg\u003C/strong\u003E - Combines both incorrect magnitude and direction\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis pressure reduction is normally compensated for by autoregulatory mechanisms to maintain cerebral perfusion. The same hydrostatic principle explains why blood pressure is higher in the feet when standing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Hydrostatic pressure is directly proportional to fluid density, gravitational acceleration, and height of the fluid column.","The hydrostatic pressure equation is P = \u03c1gh, where \u03c1 is fluid density, g is gravitational acceleration, and h is height of the fluid column (vertical distance between heart and brain).","Blood pressure differences between body positions are explained by hydrostatic forces."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94985"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17153"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94985","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94985"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-08T16:52:42+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-08T16:53:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9843"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112953"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attrib